{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488263","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488263"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:34:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"397"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/397"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.67,0.1,0.13,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97092"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79695"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"379"},{"type":"tags","id":"1153"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2531"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2764"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11264"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11275"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33142"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97092"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of double vision following a car accident where she hit her head on the steering wheel. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her head is tilted to the left. When her head is straightened, the right eye is turned up and inward. There is no ptosis or pupillary abnormality. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Left abducens nerve palsy","Right trochlear nerve palsy","Left trochlear nerve palsy","Right oculomotor nerve palsy","Left oculomotor nerve palsy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of a trochlear nerve (cranial nerve IV) palsy following head trauma. The trochlear nerve (CN IV) has the longest intracranial course of all the cranial nerves supplying the eye muscles. As such, it is highly vulnerable to trauma. The trochlear nerve supplies the contralateral superior oblique muscle, which is responsible for depression of the eye in adduction as well as intorsion. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight trochlear nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct diagnosis based on the clinical findings. When this nerve is damaged, the affected eye will deviate superiorly and medially due to unopposed action of the inferior oblique muscle. Patients typically develop a compensatory head tilt away from the affected side (in this case, tilting to the left) to minimise diplopia by reducing the vertical misalignment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough the trochlear nerve is supplied from the 4th nucleus on the contra-lateral side, damage to the nerve itself with affect the ipsilateral side as the neurons have decussated at the level of the nerve. Therefore, a \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft trochlear nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E would affect the left superior oblique muscle. An upper motor neuron lesion affecting the 4th nucleus could cause issues with the right superior oblique, but not a lower motor neuron lesion, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight \u003C/strong\u003Eand\u003Cstrong\u003E left oculomotor nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve III) typically presents with ptosis, pupillary dilation, and the affected eye positioned \u0022down and out\u0022 due to unopposed action of the lateral rectus and superior oblique muscles. These features are not present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeft abducens nerve palsy\u003C/strong\u003E (cranial nerve VI) would result in impaired abduction of the left eye, causing the eye to be pulled medially due to unopposed action of the medial rectus. This would not cause the upward deviation seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Trochlear nerve palsy is characterised by vertical diplopia, hypertropia of the affected eye, and compensatory head tilt away from the affected side.","The trochlear nerve innervates the superior oblique muscle, which depresses the eye when adducted and provides intorsion.","Trochlear nerve injury is common in head trauma due to its long intracranial course."],"references":["Blumenfeld, Hal. Neuroanatomy Through Clinical Cases. Sunderland, Mass. Sinauer Associates, 2010.","Diora JR, Plager DA. Sudden-onset trochlear nerve palsy: clinical characteristics and treatment implications. Journal of American Association for Pediatric Ophthalmology and Strabismus. 2019;23(6):321.e1-.e5. Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S1091853119305361"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79695"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"397"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79695","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79695"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-04T17:04:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-04T17:04:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id"